Anonymous Thu 05 Aug 2021 18:25:22 No.40695166 Report
Quoted By:
>>40694913
By pacing I suppose I'm reacting to filler material. You seem to write things out as though you were telling a story IRL and that lends itself to stream of consciousness commentary that usually gets culled in an editing pass.
>He isn’t annoyed by that stuff, his friend is cool in other stuff, and over the time he’s grown an interest in those rituals he speaks about.
>It's not an overly annoying quirk, and they share other interests. Eventually, the relationship created an interest in his friend's wierd "rituals".
I'm not the greatest writer but you can simplify things a bit by not asserting so much, but implying the assertion. Also avoid repeating words like "things" or "stuff".
For dialogue, there's a big difference between how written dialogue is read and spoken dialogue is heard. Read a tv or movie script and you can tell something is off about it, because it's intended to be heard not read. You can help this a bit, ironically, by reading your works aloud to yourself. If it both sounds and reads well, it's probably good dialogue.
